THE LONG TERM GOAL OF THIS PROJECT IS TO OBSERVE AND IMPROVE UNDERSTANDING OF WIND FORCING AND SEA SURFACE HEIGHT VARIABILITY AT HIGH FREQUENCIES, PERIODS OF 1 TO 20 DAYS, IN THE TROPICAL OCEANS. THIS PERIOD BAND IS OF INTEREST BECAUSE THE SPACE TIME SCALES OF OCEANIC EQUATORIAL WAVES AT THESE FREQUENCIES HAVE HISTORICALLY MADE ADEQUATE OBSERVATION OF THE VARIABILITY DIFFICULT; THESE WAVES HAVE ZONAL SCALES THAT ARE VERY LARGE, EXCEEDING 3000 KM, AND MERIDIONAL SCALES THAT ARE RELATIVELY SHORT, APPROXIMATELY 100 KM, MAKING ADEQUATE IN SITU MEASUREMENTS TOO COSTLY, AND THE SHORT TEMPORAL SCALES POSE CHALLENGES FOR OBSERVATION WITH SATELLITE ALTIMETERS BECAUSE THE WAVE PERIODS ARE SHORT COMPARED TO ORBIT REPEAT PERIODS. AS A RESULT, THERE HAS BEEN RELATIVELY LITTLE PROGRESS SINCE THE EARLY 1980S IN OBSERVING AND UNDERSTANDING EQUATORIAL INERTIA GRAVITY AND MIXED ROSSBY GRAVITY WAVES AND THEIR RESPONSE TO WIND FORCING. HOWEVER, WITH CAREFUL CONSIDERATION OF THE SATELLITE SAMPLING, IT IS POSSIBLE TO EXPLOIT THE LONG ZONAL LENGTH SCALES OF THESE HIGH FREQUENCY EQUATORIAL WAVES IN AN ANALYSIS OF SATELLITE SCATTEROMETER AND ALTIMETER DATA, OPENING UP NEW OPPORTUNITIES TO LEARN ABOUT THE PROPERTIES AND DYNAMICS OF THESE WAVES. THIS WORK SEEKS TO EXTEND THE INVESTIGATORS PREVIOUS WORK DONE ESTIMATING AND INTERPRETING THE WAVENUMBER FREQUENCY SPECTRAL PROPERTIES OF THE OCEANIC EQUATORIAL WAVES AND THE WIND FORCING THAT DRIVES THEM. ONE GOAL IS TO EXTEND ANALYSIS OF OCEANIC EQUATORIAL WAVES IN THE 4 TO 20 DAY PERIOD BAND FROM THE SPECTRAL DOMAIN INTO THE TIME SPACE DOMAIN TO ADDRESS QUESTIONS ON THE SPACE TIME VARIABILITY OF THE WAVES AND THEIR FORCING. A SECOND GOAL IS TO EXTEND WORK DONE IN ANALYZING THE RESOLUTION CAPABILITY OF THE SATELLITE SCATTEROMETER SAMPLING, AND THE ERRORS RESULTING FROM POORLY RESOLVED BUT ENERGETIC VARIABILITY, TO QUANTITATIVELY EXAMINE THE RELATIVE MERITS OF DIFFERENT APPROACHES TO ESTIMATING THE LARGE SCALE DIURNAL WIND SIGNAL FROM COMBINATIONS OF RECENTLY INITIATED SCATTEROMETER MISSIONS. WE WILL ALSO WORK TO QUANTIFY THE REDUCTION IN ALIASING AND SAMPLING ERRORS IN GRIDDED WIND PRODUCTS THAT RESULT FROM BETTER RESOLUTION OF THE DIURNAL WIND SIGNAL. THE PROPOSED WORK WOULD USE SATELLITE SCATTEROMETER AND ALTIMETER DATA IN A NOVEL WAY TO ALLOW NEW INSIGHT INTO THE PROPERTIES AND DYNAMICS OF WIND AND SEA SURFACE HEIGHT VARIABILITY AT HIGH FREQUENCIES, PERIODS OF 1 TO 20 DAYS, A PERIOD BAND THAT HAS NOT PREVIOUSLY BEEN WELL OBSERVED BY THESE SATELLITE INSTRUMENTS.

doc.ContractDescription: A HIGH RESOLUTION GLOBAL ANALYSIS OF OCEAN SURFACE VECTOR WINDS WAS DEVELOPED BY THE OBJECTIVELY ANALYZED AIR SEA FLUXES OAFLUX PROJECT LED BY THE PI. THE ANALYSIS COVERS THE ENTIRE SATELLITE WIND OBSERVING PERIOD JULY 1987 TO THE PRESENT AND IS A SYNERGY OF 12 SATELLITE SENSORS, INCLUDING 2 SCATTEROMETERS QUIKSCAT AND ASCAT, AND 10 PASSIVE MICROWAVE RADIOMETERS AMSRE, 6 SSMI SENSORS, 2 SSMIS SENSORS, WINDSAT ONLY WIND SPEED RETRIEVALS WERE USED. HOWEVER, ONE INTRIGUING ISSUE HAS ARISEN DURING THE DEVELOPMENT, THAT IS, OAFLUX DIFFERS CONSIDERABLY FROM QUIKSCAT IN THE WIND STRESS CURL PATTERN ASSOCIATED WITH THE GULF STREAM FRONTS, ALTHOUGH OAFLUX INCLUDES QUIKSCAT IN THE SYNTHESIS. OUR QUEST FOR AN ANSWER HAS LED TO A SURPRISED FINDING. ELIMINATION OF RAIN CONTAMINATED WIND VECTOR CELLS WVCS IN QUIKSCAT APPEARS TO HAVE A BIAS EFFECT NOT ONLY ON QUIKSCAT WIND STRESS DERIVATIVE FIELDS AT OCEAN FRONTS, BUT ALSO ON THE DECADAL TENDENCY OF THE QUIKSCAT 10YEAR TIME SERIES. OSCAT IS AFFECTED IN A SIMILAR WAY AT OCEAN FRONTS. THE SOURCE OF THE RAIN BIAS IS THE SYNOPTIC WEATHER SYSTEMS IN THE MID LATITUDE STORM TRACK REGIONS AND THE TROPICAL RAIN BELTS OF THE ITCZ AND SPCZ. AS THE WVCS AFFECTED BY RAIN ARE ASSOCIATED WITH CYCLONIC WIND STRESS CURLS, THE FREQUENT OCCURRENCE OF RAIN AT THESE PREFERRED REGIONS CAUSES A PERSISTENT REMOVAL OF CYCLONIC CURLS. ELIMINATION OF RAIN FLAGGED WIND RETRIEVALS IS DEEMED AS A PREREQUISITE FOR SUCCESSFUL APPLICATIONS OF THE KUBAND SCATTEROMETER WINDS. THE QUESTIONS WE HAVE ARE WHETHER THE INCLUSION OF RAIN FLAGGED WVCS IN KUBAND SCATTEROMETERS WILL HAVE MORE BENEFITS THAN WE KNOW COULD RAIN CONTAMINATED WVCS IN KUBAND SCATTEROMETERS BE IMPROVED THROUGH CROSS VALIDATION WITH SENSORS OPERATING AT LOWER FREQUENCIES HOW CAN WE EVALUATE THE VARIOUS MULTI SENSOR VECTOR WIND PRODUCTS, WHICH USE DIFFERENT MEANS TO RECOVER THE RAIN CONTAMINATED WVCS MISSING DATA BUT THE DIFFERENCES IN THE MEANS AFFECT THE WIND ESTIMATES ON SYNOPTIC AND MESOSCALES AND ON LOW FREQUENCY DECADAL AND LONGER TIMESCALE VARIATIONS THESE QUESTIONS HAVE NO STRAIGHTFORWARD ANSWERS, AS THEY REQUIRE COLLABORATIVE EFFORTS AMONG SATELLITE DATA RECORD DEVELOPERS, RESEARCHERS WHO USE SATELLITE DERIVED WIND PRODUCTS, AND ALGORITHM DEVELOPERS WHO WORK ON RAIN ALGORITHM REFINEMENT. ON THE INDIVIDUAL LEVEL, WE PROPOSE THE FOLLOWING FIVE SPECIFIC RESEARCH FOCI AS OUR CONTRIBUTION TO IMPROVING THE KNOWLEDGE AND UNDERSTANDING OF THESE QUESTIONS. THREE RESEARCH FOCI ARE TO ADDRESS TECHNICAL CHALLENGES I GLOBAL CHARACTERIZATION OF THE EFFECT OF RAIN BIAS IN KUBAND SCATTEROMETERS, II ENHANCEMENT OF OAFLUX TIME SERIES BY INCLUDING OSCAT AND ASCATB AND IMPROVING THE ESTIMATION AND UNCERTAINTY ANALYSIS OF NEAR SURFACE WINDS ASSOCIATED WITH SYNOPTIC STORMS, AND III IDENTIFICATION OF THE STRENGTHS AND WEAKNESSES IN OAFLUX, SCATTEROMETERS, AND OTHER SATELLITE BASED PRODUCTS IN REGIONAL AND GLOBAL APPLICATIONS. MEANWHILE, TWO RESEARCH FOCI ARE PROPOSED TO ADDRESS THE TECHNICAL CHALLENGES THROUGH SCIENTIFIC APPLICATIONS IV INVESTIGATION OF THE POTENTIAL SHIFT OF THE MEAN ITCZ LATITUDE POSITION AND ITS RELATION TO THE STRENGTHENING OF THE TROPICAL TRADE WIND SYSTEM, AND V INVESTIGATION OF THE COLLOCATION OF THE ANTARCTIC CIRCUMPOLAR CURRENT ACC FRONTS AND THE ZERO LINE OF WIND STRESS CURL AT MAJOR TOPOGRAPHIC OBSTRUCTIONS IS IT TOPOGRAPHIC CONTROLLED COUPLING OR A MANIFESTATION OF SURFACE CURRENTS ON SATELLITE WIND RETRIEVALS CLIMATE RESEARCH DEMANDS MORE THAN EVER A CLIMATE RECORD OF OCEAN SURFACE VECTOR WINDS TO ADDRESS PRESSING LONG TERM CHANGES IN THE ATMOSPHERE OCEAN SYSTEM. THE EXPECTED SIGNIFICANCE OF THE PROPOSED RESEARCH IS IN THE POTENTIAL TO RECTIFY AND IMPROVE THE RAIN BIAS EFFECT ON THE MULTI SENSOR SYNTHESIS AND TO ADVANCE TOWARD A HIGH QUALITY OCEAN VECTOR WIND CLIMATE RECORD WITH ACCURACY AND FIDELITY THAT MEET THE NEEDS FOR CLIMATE DETECTION AND ATTRIBUTION.

MANIPULATION INVOLVES MAKING AND BREAKING CONTACTS WITH PARTS OF THE ENVIRONMENT. IT IS ESSENTIALLY A PERCEPTUAL PROBLEM IN WHICH FEEDBACK ACQUIRED BEFORE, DURING AND AFTER CONTACT FORMATION GUIDES THE PLACEMENT OF CONTACTS AND THE APPLICATION OF FORCES. THE RESEARCH PROJECT DEVELOPS THE ROLE OF INFORMATION GATHERING IN ROBOT GRASPING. WE FORMULATE A UNIFORM TREATMENT OF VISUAL AND TACTILE OBSERVERS THAT ARE SELECTED BY VIRTUE OF EXPECTED INFORMATION GAIN WITH RESPECT TO MANIPULATION GOALS. TO DO SO, WE DEVELOP A CONTROL THEORETIC FRAMEWORK FOR SEARCHING FOR AND TRACKING SENSORY INVARIANTS IN VISION AND HAPTIC FEEDBACK, ESTIMATE STATE USING THE DYNAMIC RESPONSE OF GROUPS OF THESE CONTROL PROCESSES, AND CONSTRUCT MODELS OF OBJECTS IN TERMS OF CONSTELLATIONS OF THESE CONTROL EVENTS. OUR PROPOSAL EXTENDS PREVIOUS WORK IN SENSOR-DRIVEN GRASP CONTROL TO ENGAGE CONTINUOUS TACTILE AND VISUAL FEEDBACK TO FORM, VERIFY, AND REFINE GRASPS. WE PROPOSE PROBABILISTIC MODELS OF OBJECTS THAT RELATE VISUAL FEEDBACK TO INVARIANTS GROUNDED IN TACTILE DATA AND ADDRESS AUTONOMOUS SYSTEMS THAT LEARN THE MODELS ALONG WITH CUMULATIVE MANIPULATION SKILLS. CONTROL ORGANIZATION ALLOWS PLANNERS TO CONSIDER THE ENTIRE DISPOSITION OF THE ROBOT: ITS HANDS; ARMS; LOCATION; AND THE POSTURE OF ITS SENSORS AND LIMBS RELATIVE TO OBJECTS TO FIND MANIPULATION STRATEGIES. THE PROPOSAL AIMS AT TWO PRINCIPLE GOALS. (1) TO USE AUTONOMOUS, HAPTICALLY-GUIDED GRASP CONTROL TECHNIQUES TO FUNNEL CONTACT CONFIGURATIONS INTO THOSE THAT SATISFY NECESSARY CONDITIONS FOR FORCE CLOSURE. THIS APPROACH GENERATES ALL CANDIDATE GRASP CONFIGURATIONS, ARM GOALS, AND HAND PRESHAPES THAT FUNNEL INTO PARTICULAR CANDIDATE GRASPS WITHOUT ASSUMING SPECIFIC MANIPULATION GOALS A PRIORI. THIS APPROACH LEVERAGES POWERFUL HAPTIC STRUCTURE DURING ON-LINE GRASP EXPLORATION AND DRAMATICALLY REDUCES THE NUMBER OF LEARNING TRIALS REQUIRED TO ACQUIRE THE VISUAL AFFORDANCES OF GRASPING IN THE COURSE OF ON-LINE INTERACTIONS WITH OBJECTS. (2) TO EXPLOIT OBJECT MODELS AND HISTORIES OF VISUAL AND TACTILE OBSERVATIONS TO MAXIMIZE THE EXPECTED INFORMATION GAIN OF ELECTIVE CONTROL ACTIONS RELATIVE TO THE TASK. THE RESULT IS A NEW, INTEGRATED, AUTONOMOUS MANIPULATION CONTROL FRAMEWORK THAT ACQUIRES MODELS AND ADAPTS AT RUN-TIME TO OBJECTS AND (UNANTICIPATED) RUN-TIME CONDITIONS. MOTOR ELEMENTS (CALLED SEARCHTRACK PROGRAMS) COMBINE CONTROL AND PROBABILISTIC MODELING PRIMITIVES. COMPOSITIONS OF THESE PRIMITIVES YIELD TEMPORALLY EXTENDED MOTOR ACTIONS THAT ALSO INFLUENCE POSTERIORS OVER BELIEF IN THE STATE OF THE SYSTEM. OBJECT MODELS TAKE THE FORM OF DYNAMIC BAYES NETS (DBN) THAT FUSE THE HISTORY OF PAST OBSERVATIONS AND ACCUMULATE OPTIMAL ESTIMATES OF STATE EXPRESSED IN TERMS OF PROBABILISTICALLY DEPENDENT "CONTROL AFFORDANCES" WITH GEOMETRIC ATTRIBUTES. WE FORMULATE AN APPROACH TO PLANNING THAT RESOLVES AMBIGUITY BY REASONING OVER EXPECTED INFORMATION GAIN TO GENERATE HIGH-QUALITY INTERACTION HISTORIES. THE RESULT IS A UNIFORM TREATMENT OF MANUAL AND PERCEPTUAL ACTIONS THAT SIMULTANEOUSLY REFINE STATE INFORMATION AND MANIPULATE THE ENVIRONMENT TO CONFORM WITH GOAL STATES IN UNSTRUCTURED ENVIRONMENTS. THE MODELS WE INTRODUCE REPRESENT A UNIQUE AND NATURAL UNIFICATION OF CONTROL, OPTIMAL ESTIMATORS FOR PARTIALLY OBSERVABLE SYSTEMS, MANIPULATION CONTROL, AND PLANNING. THE STUDY YIELDS AUTONOMOUS ROBOT MANIPULATION SYSTEMS WITH A COMPREHENSIVE LIBRARY OF BASIC SKILLS THAT ARE SUPPORTED BY AN ARRAY OF OBJECT MODELS THAT TOGETHER IMPLEMENT MOTOR SKILLS IN NOVEL RUN-TIME SITUATIONS. WE PLAN TO CONSTRUCT EXPERT SENSORY AND MOTOR KNOWLEDGE OF ~100 OBJECTS, TO DEMONSTRATE THE USE OF KNOWLEDGE AND SKILL TO PLAN MANIPULATION STRATEGIES IN UNSTRUCTURED, MULTI-OBJECT SCENARIOS, AND TO TRANSFER THIS TECHNOLOGY AT TRL 6 TO ROBONAUT 2 AT THE JOHNSON SPACE CENTER IN HOUSTON, TEXAS. OPTION YEARS (4-5) CONCERN THE EXTENSION OF THESE NEW FUNCTIONS TO MULTI-BODY ASSEMBLY TASKS.

doc.ContractDescription: MERGERS AND INTERACTIONS HAVE PROFOUND EFFECTS ON THE EVOLUTION OF GALAXIES AND ON THE VARIOUS PHYSICAL PROCESSES ASSOCIATED WITH STAR FORMATION AND THE FUELING OF ACTIVE NUCLEI (AGN). THERE REMAINS, HOWEVER, AN INCOMPLETE UNDERSTANDING OF HOW INTERACTIONS AFFECT SUCH PROCESSES OR HOW IMPORTANT THEY ARE IN CONTROLLING THE APPEARANCE OF TODAY'S UNIVERSE. WE PROPOSE TO STUDY 180 INTERACTING GALAXIES IN 101 SYSTEMS SPANNING EARLY TO LATE STAGE MERGERS FOR WHICH NEWLY ARCHIVED NASA DATA ENABLE DETAILED ANALYSES OF THEIR ULTRAVIOLET-TO-FAR INFRARED (UV-FIR) SPECTRAL ENERGY DISTRIBUTIONS (SEDS). OUR GOAL IS AN IMPROVED UNDERSTANDING OF HOW A WIDE RANGE OF KEY GALAXY PARAMETERS VARY ACROSS THE INTERACTION SEQUENCE. OUR DERIVED PHYSICAL PARAMETERS WILL INCLUDE THE TOTAL OPTICALINFRARED LUMINOSITY, STAR FORMATION RATE, SPECIFIC STAR FORMATION RATE, STELLAR MASS, DUST TEMPERATURES AND DUST MASSES, COMPACTNESS, PHOTO-DISSOCIATION REGION (PDR) FRACTIONS, AND AGN CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE FIR SED. OUR SAMPLE IS TAKEN FROM THE KEEL-KENNICUTT CATALOG OF MERGING GALAXIES (BASED ONLY ON APPARENT GALAXY SEPARATIONS AND HENCE FREE OF MORPHOLOGICAL BIAS) AND THE SURACE IRAS SAMPLE OF BRIGHT MERGERS. OUR SAMPLE CONTAINS VIRTUALLY ALL BRIGHT MERGERS WITH UV-FIR DATA IN THE ARCHIVES, INCLUDING (BUT NOT LIMITED TO) DATA FROM MISSIONS GALEX, SWIFT, SPITZER, WISE, AND HERSCHEL. WE WILL RE-REDUCE, RECALIBRATE, AND EXTRACT THE PHOTOMETRY IN UP TO 23 WAVELENGTH BANDS FROM THE UV TO THE FIR. OUR ANALYSIS PLAN EMPHASIZES THREE NEW SED MODELING TOOLS, ONE OF WHICH WE HAVE RECENTLY DEVELOPED. NEARLY ALL OF THE SOURCES ALSO HAVE SPITZER IRS SPECTRAL DATA (PRIMARILY OF THE CIRCUMNUCLEAR REGIONS), AND WE WILL USE THE IRS DATA TO SUPPLEMENT THE SED CONCLUSIONS VIA OUR OWN ALGORITHM WHICH ALSO INFERS METALLICITY, INTERSTELLAR MEDIUM (ISM) AMBIENT PRESSURE, AND EMBEDDED YOUNG STAR FRACTIONS. FINALLY, WE WILL COMPARE EACH MERGER TO THE SIMULATED PHOTOMETRY/ MORPHOLOGY OF A SUITE OF SIMULATIONS BASED ON HERNQUIST ET AL. MODELS. SEDS FOR THE SIMULATIONS WILL BE CALCULATED IN EACH CASE USING THE SUNRISE RADIATIVE TRANSFER CODE. WE WILL IDENTIFY THE SIMULATION AND INTERACTING STAGE/AGE THAT BEST REPRODUCES EACH OBSERVED MERGER'S PROPERTIES. THE RESULTS WILL ALLOW US TO REFINE AND TEST HOW PHYSICAL PARAMETERS DEVELOP IN MERGERS OF VARIOUS KINDS, AS WELL AS HELP TEST THE RELIABILITY OF THE SIMULATION ASSUMPTIONS. WE WILL IN ADDITION ANALYZE 25 NON-INTERACTING GALAXIES AS COMPARISONS. WE HAVE ALREADY SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETED THE ANALYSES SUITE ON A SUBSET OF 31 GALAXIES IN 14 MERGER GROUPS. THIS INITIAL SET CONTAINED ALL THE KEEL-KENNICUTT MERGERS FOR WHICH SUITABLE HERSCHEL DATA WERE IN THE ARCHIVE WHEN THE PROJECT BEGAN SEVERAL YEARS AGO. OUR CONCLUSIONS, PUBLISHED IN LANZ ET AL. (2013), DEMONSTRATE THE POWER OF THE TECHNIQUES TO TRACE PHYSICAL ACTIVITY ACROSS THE MERGER SEQUENCE. THE CONCLUSIONS, HOWEVER, WERE LIMITED BY THE SMALL NUMBERS. TODAY THE AVAILABLE DATASET IS MUCH LARGER AND, WITH THE END OF HERSCHEL, IS IN SOME SENSE COMPLETE. WE PROPOSE A FOCUSED EFFORT TO EXTEND OUR WORK TO THE LARGE SAMPLE DESCRIBED. THE MUCH LARGER SAMPLE WILL ENABLE US TO REACH MUCH FIRMER STATISTICAL CONCLUSIONS, AND TO ADDRESS THE PROCESSES IN INTERMEDIATE INTERACTION STAGES ACROSS A WIDER RANGE OF GALAXY MASS-RATIOS AND IMPACT PARAMETERS. OUR CATALOG OF ~23-BAND UV-FIR PHOTOMETRY ON THESE 180 (+25) GALAXIES WILL CONSTITUTE A LEGACY CONTRIBUTION. OUR CONCLUSIONS WILL HAVE APPLICATION FOR MERGERS IN THE MORE DISTANT UNIVERSE. OUR TEAM IS EXPERT IN THE IMPORTANT AND DIFFICULT ISSUES OF DATA REDUCTION AND ANALYSIS IN THE MANY BANDS REQUIRED FOR THIS PROJECT, IN MODELING AND USING BAYESIAN AND OTHER METHODS TO OBTAIN THE BEST FITS TO THE OBSERVATIONS FROM MULTI-COMPONENT GALAXY MODELS, IN THE SIMULATIONS, AND IN UNDERSTANDING PHYSICAL PROCESSES IN GALAXIES.
